The latest update from the African Union on the coronavirus in the African continent indicates that new cases have been reported in some countries. Kenya has not been listed among the 11 countries with the virus but has been featured in the countries that have reported persons under investigation (PUI) for COVID-19. The update released on March 10 shows that 33 countries out of 55 have reported persons under investigation. A total of 105 cases have been reported in African countries. According to the report, 10 countries in Africa had reported a positive test for the virus, the latest being the Democratic Republic of Congo. The 10 countries with the virus include Egypt, Algeria, Burkina Faso, Cameroon, Morocco, Nigeria, Senegal, South Africa, Togo and Tunisia. Egypt has reported the highest cases in the continent with 59 cases followed by Algeria which has 20 confirmed cases. The outbreak of coronavirus was first reported from Wuhan, China, on December 31, 2019. Since the outbreak, 3,810 deaths relating to the virus have been reported out of which 3,123 have been reported from mainland China. To date, 687 total deaths have been reported outside China. A total of 109,575 suspected cases have been reported worldwide. Italy is the second most hit country after China and has reported more than 10,000 infections. The government of Kenya has taken measures to its citizens from the virus. The government banned international meetings in the country which has more than 15 people as one of the measures.